{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>This entry represents chitin synthases classes I, II and III [ec:2.4.1.16] from fungi, in which chitin is an essential component of the cell wall and it is synthesised on the cytoplasmic surface of the cell membrane by membrane bound chitin synthases [[cite:PUB00096620], [cite:PUB00096626], [cite:PUB00005534]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false} {"text" "<p>Chitin synthase ([ec:2.4.1.16]), also known as chitin-UDP acetyl-glucosaminyl transferase, is a plasma membrane-bound protein which catalyses the conversion of UDP-N-acettyl-D-glucosamine and  {(1,4)-(N-acetyl- beta-D-glucosaminyl)}(N) to UDP and {(1,4)-(N-acetyl-beta-D-\nglucosaminyl)}(N+1) to produce chitin, an abundant biopolymer found in a diverse group of organisms, ranging from fungal species to insects and crustaceans [[cite:PUB00096620]]. Chitin synthases are grouped into six classes (I-VI), classes I to III comprise one family, which are smaller proteins (average 900 amino acids) and classes IV to VI comprise a second family whose proteins have an average size of nearly 1,200 amino acids [[cite:PUB00096620]]. It plays a major role in cell wall biogenesis in fungi, as chitin is crucial for the maintenance of cell morphology [[cite:PUB00096626], [cite:PUB00096627]] and in C. elegans is essential during embryogenesis providing mechanical support and chemical impermeability [[cite:PUB00096621], [cite:PUB00096622]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure nil, :overlaps-with nil, :member-databases {"pfam" {"PF01644" "Chitin synthase"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Fungal chitin synthase", "short" "Chitin_synth_fun"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 21, "domain_architectures" 171, "proteomes" 1264, "taxa" 4191, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions" 0, "matches" 8789, "sets" 0, "proteins" 8751, "structural_models" {"alphafold" 5887}, "p